# TypeScript Patterns

## No `any`

Avoid `any`; use `unknown` + type guard or Zod for untrusted input.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function parsePayload(data: any): Patient {
  return data as Patient;
}

// ✅ GOOD – unknown + type guard
function parsePayload(data: unknown): Patient {
  const parsed = patientSchema.parse(data);
  return parsed;
}

// ✅ GOOD – unknown + narrowing
function isPatient(obj: unknown): obj is Patient {
  return typeof obj === 'object' && obj !== null && 'id' in obj && 'name' in obj;
}
```

## Explicit Return Types

Use explicit return types on public functions and exported functions.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
export function formatDate(date: Date): string {
  return date.toLocaleDateString('pt-BR');
}

export async function getPatient(id: string): Promise<Patient | null> {
  const { data } = await supabase.from('patients').select('*').eq('id', id).maybeSingle();
  return data;
}

// ❌ BAD – inferência implícita em funções públicas
export function formatDate(date: Date) {
  return date.toLocaleDateString('pt-BR');
}
```

Exception: simple callbacks and lambdas can rely on inference: `items.map(x => x.id)`.

## `interface` vs `type`

| Use | When |
|-----|------|
| `interface` | Object shapes; extends; declaration merging |
| `type` | Unions, primitives, tuples, mapped types |

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD – interface para objetos
interface Patient {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  birth_date: string | null;
}

// ✅ GOOD – type para unions
type Status = 'active' | 'closed';

// ✅ GOOD – type para primitives
type UserPhone = string;

// ✅ GOOD – type para tuples
type Coordinate = [number, number];

// ✅ GOOD – interface quando precisa estender
interface PatientWithCase extends Patient {
  case_id: string;
}
```
